I got out for a number of reasons, but it wasn't all at once.
Being queer was one big issue. Between school years in college I actually went to a conversion therapy place for the summer.
Oh fuck
Not as terrible as you'd think, but I definitely lucked out. I've heard horror stories. The place I went actually focused mostly on individual counseling and was more or less a positive experience.

And they used to be worse. They had recently made a rule that people under 18 couldn't go through the program because they'd had too many parents handcuff their kids in the car and drive them down and dump them there.
Reddit was another big deconcerter and helped break the fundamentalist bubble I had growb up in.
Deconverter*
There’s a reason so many fundamentalists are anti education
And anti-birth control. That's how they trap women
My wife teaches at a religious school and at least once a year has a parent blow off a concern she has because “oh she’ll be fine, girls don’t need that much education.”
Mhm. I was partly home schooled.
Also, private Christian school. I did go to public high school, but it was tiny. And then, obviously, Bible College.

Weed became a gateway exit, but I also became a huge, unproductive pothead. Really I was just medicating my pain.

I'm on the other side of that now, and smoke rarely.

Oh, the other major exit event was when I was a missionary in Europe and saw one of our friends who was 16 die by falling off the roof of our apartment. I wrote up a lengthy blog post about that, if you're interested I can email it to you. Spoiler alert: it's depressing af

I think it's a good piece because it sort of refutes the "no atheists in a foxhole" trope but not in a smug way. Writing about loss of faith that isn't smug is rare
I struggle not being smug or condescending about religion

I've become a lot more smug since then. At the time I was really struggling with religion, spirituality and existentialism. It felt like drowning. It probably wouldn't hurt to lose some smugness.
Religious people are super smug, too, so it's hard not to mirror their shitty behavior
Yeah, I had years of practice being a smug religious person

Not a religious person myself, but I always found it funny that the people who believe that there is nothing at death but decomposing are often smug about it. It's a really...dark thing to think about

"ha, you believe in some eternal life for your spirit? Foolish simpleton. Hmm myself? Well obviously I believe in the truth, that absolutely nothing happens when you die, nothing but a sea of eternal darkness, but you're not even councious enough to be aware of it. Just poof. Like a light switch, only difference is you cant turn it back on"
Again, not making fun of the actual belief of atheism, not religious myself... just its a really... really odd subject to watch people brag about
Nothing else really I believe in besides this that I hope I'm really...really wrong about
Lol, well, you may hope you're wrong, but don't hope that evangelicals are right.

I'm not sure it's smugness about the permanence of death so much as it is about believing in unprovable nonsense from a magic book. I'm smug about flat earthers too but there's nothing ironic about me not believing in the wonder of flat earth theory

Regarding religion, I’m wary of anyone, fervent or religious, who claims to have the answers. If you have answers then you stop asking questions. No one knows one way or another whether there is something greater than ourselves out there. Is it the Christian/Islamic/Jewish/etc. idea? No.Atheists? Nope. Saying there is nothing is having an answer they don’t actually have.

The “befores” and “afters” are very reminiscent of your writing, and the event in the middle is alarmingly similar. A very good story about how to reconcile ourselves with the fact that there are significant questions we will never learn the answers to.
